# Adjacent Residual Minimum

## Solution 1 - Brute Force Approach

### Intuition


- At every step, we can remove elements only from the ends, so the problem naturally depends on a subarray defined by left and right indices.

2. Since each operation removes exactly two elements, the problem reduces in size gradually while accumulating score.

3. Different choices at each step can lead to different future possibilities, so we must explore all options to get the maximum score.

4. This forms an overlapping subproblem structure where the same subarray ranges may be solved multiple times.


### Approach

- Use recursion to represent the current state with two pointers indicating the active subarray.

- At each step, try all three valid removal operations and compute their resulting scores recursively.

- Add the current operation’s score to the result of the recursive call on the reduced subarray.

- Return the maximum score among all possible choices to ensure the optimal result.

### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
maximizeLineupScore(values) {
    /* Start recursion on full array */
    return solve(values, 0, length(values) - 1)
}

solve(values, left, right) {
    /* If size of current segment is <= 2, no operation allowed */
    if (right - left + 1 <= 2) {
        return 0
    }
    /* Option 1: remove first two elements */
    op1 = values[left] + values[left + 1] + solve(values, left + 2, right)
    /* Option 2: remove last two elements */
    op2 = values[right] + values[right - 1] + solve(values, left, right - 2)
    /* Option 3: remove first and last elements */
    op3 = values[left] + values[right] + solve(values, left + 1, right - 1)
    /* Return maximum score among all choices */
    return maximum(op1, op2, op3)
}
```

</CodeBlock>


