# Threshold Frequency Substrings

## Solution 1 - Brute Force Approach

### Intuition

* A substring is valid if at least one character appears `threshold` times or more

* Instead of recomputing frequencies from scratch, we build them incrementally as we expand the substring

* For every starting index, extending the substring helps reuse previous frequency counts efficiently

* Checking all substrings ensures we don’t miss any valid combination


### Approach

* Fix a starting index and maintain a frequency array for characters

* Expand the substring one character at a time and update its frequency

* After each extension, check if any character frequency reaches the threshold

* Count all such substrings and return the final total


### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
countResonantClips(recording, threshold) {
    /*
       recording is a string of length n
       We count all substrings where at least one character
       appears at least 'threshold' times
    */
    n = length of recording
    ans = 0
    /* Try all possible starting points */
    for (i from 0 to n - 1) {
        /* Frequency array for 26 lowercase letters */
        freq = array of size 26 initialized to 0
        /* Expand substring from i to end */
        for (j from i to n - 1) {
            /* Update frequency of current character */
            ch = recording[j]
            freq[ch - 'a'] = freq[ch - 'a'] + 1
            /* Check if current substring is valid */
            if (isPossible(freq, threshold)) {
                ans = ans + 1
            }
        }
    }
    return ans
}

isPossible(freq, k) {
    /*
       Check if any character appears at least k times
    */
    for (i from 0 to 25) {
        if (freq[i] >= k) {
            return true
        }
    }
    return false
}
```

