## Solution 2 - Optimal Approach

### Intuition

* A valid segment must contain **all occurrences** of every character that appears inside it. So if we include any character, the segment must cover from that character’s first occurrence to its last occurrence.

* Because of this, a valid segment can only start at the **first occurrence** of its starting character. If it starts later, that character already has an occurrence outside the segment, so it can never be valid.

* While extending a segment from such a start, every new character we meet may force the segment’s ending position to move further right up to that character’s last occurrence.

* If during this process we meet a character whose first occurrence is before the current start, then the segment can never be valid. But whenever our current index reaches the required ending point, we have found a valid exclusive segment.

### Approach

* First, store the first and last occurrence of every character in the string.

* Try each index as a possible starting point of the segment, but only if that index is the first occurrence of its character.

* From this start, move to the right and keep building the segment.

* Whenever a new character appears, extend the segment end to include that character’s last occurrence, because all its occurrences must stay inside the segment.

* If at any point we see a character whose first occurrence is before the chosen start, stop immediately because that character already has an occurrence outside the segment, so this segment cannot be valid.

* Whenever the current position reaches the current segment end, it means all characters seen so far are fully contained inside `[start, end]`, so this is a valid segment.

* If this valid segment is not the entire string, update the maximum answer.

* After trying all valid starts, return the maximum length found, or `-1` if no proper valid segment exists.

### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
longestExclusiveSegment(text) {
    n = length of text
    /* Store first occurrence of each character, initially set to n */
    first = list of size 26 filled with n
    /* Store last occurrence of each character, initially set to -1 */
    last = list of size 26 filled with -1
    /* Compute first and last occurrence for every character */
    for (i = 0 to n - 1) {
        idx = text[i] - 'a'
        first[idx] = minimum of first[idx] and i
        last[idx] = i
    }
    /* Store the best valid segment length found so far */
    answer = -1
    /* Try every position as a possible segment start */
    for (start = 0 to n - 1) {
        startIdx = text[start] - 'a'
        /* A valid segment can only start at first occurrence of its starting character */
        if (first[startIdx] != start) {
            continue
        }
        /* Store the farthest required end of the current segment */
        end = -1
        /* Extend the segment to the right */
        for (j = start to n - 1) {
            idx = text[j] - 'a'
            /* If this character started before current segment, segment cannot be valid */
            if (first[idx] < start) {
                break
            }
            /* Include all occurrences of this character inside the segment */
            end = maximum of end and last[idx]
            /* If current index reaches end, current segment is valid */
            if (j == end) {
                length = end - start + 1
                /* Segment must not be the whole string */
                if (length < n) {
                    answer = maximum of answer and length
                }
            }
        }
    }
    /* Return the longest valid proper segment */
    return answer
}
