## Solution 2 - Optimal Approach

### Intuition

* We fix the middle element `values[j]` and try to choose the best valid left value and best valid right value around it.

* For the left side, we need the **largest value smaller than** `values[j]`, because the score contains `+ values[a]`. So a bigger valid left value gives a better answer.

* For the right side, we need the **largest value greater than** `values[j]`, because the score also contains `+ values[c]`. So we precompute suffix maximums to quickly know the best possible right value.

* A sorted set helps us maintain all values seen on the left and quickly find the best smaller one for the current middle element. Then for each `j`, we combine:
  `best left smaller value - values[j] + best right greater value`
  and keep the maximum.

### Approach

* Precompute a `suffixMax` array where `suffixMax[i]` stores the maximum value from index `i` to the end. This helps us quickly get the best possible right value for any middle index.

* Maintain a sorted set `leftValues` containing all values that appear before the current middle index `j`.

* Traverse the array by treating each position `j` as the middle element of the triplet.

* For the left side, use the sorted set to find the largest value strictly smaller than `values[j]`.

* For the right side, check whether `suffixMax[j + 1]` is strictly greater than `values[j]`. If yes, that becomes the best valid right value.

* If both a valid left value and a valid right value exist, compute the score:
  `leftBest - values[j] + rightBest`

* Keep updating the maximum answer with the best score found.

* After processing the current middle element, insert `values[j]` into the set so it becomes available for future positions.

### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
maxTripletValue(values) {
    n = length of values
    /* Create suffixMax where suffixMax[i] stores the maximum value from i to n - 1 */
    suffixMax = list of size n
    /* Last position can only see itself */
    suffixMax[n - 1] = values[n - 1]
    /* Fill suffix maximums from right to left */
    for (i = n - 2 down to 0) {
        /* Best value on the suffix is either current value or best from the right */
        suffixMax[i] = maximum of values[i] and suffixMax[i + 1]
    }
    leftValues = empty sorted set
    insert values[0] into leftValues
    answer = negative infinity
    /* Try every valid middle index */
    for (j = 1 to n - 2) {
        /* Find first value in leftValues which is greater than or equal to values[j] */
        it = lower_bound of values[j] in leftValues
        /* We need a left value strictly smaller than values[j] */
        /* Also we need a right value strictly greater than values[j] */
        if (it is not at beginning of leftValues AND suffixMax[j + 1] > values[j]) {
            /* Move to the largest value smaller than values[j] */
            move it one step left
            /* This is the best valid left value */
            leftBest = value at it
            /* Best valid right value comes from suffix maximum */
            rightBest = suffixMax[j + 1]
            /* Compute score for this triplet */
            current = leftBest - values[j] + rightBest
            /* Update maximum answer */
            answer = maximum of answer and current
        }
        /* Add current value to left side for future middle positions */
        insert values[j] into leftValues
    }
    return answer
}
