# Count Unique Visitor Segments

## Solution 1

### Intuition

- The goal is to count all substrings that contain only unique characters.

- For each starting index, we try to extend the substring as long as no duplicate appears.

- Once a duplicate character is found, further extension from that starting point becomes invalid.

- Every valid extension contributes one unique substring to the final count.

### Approach

- Iterate over all possible starting indices of substrings.

- For each start, use a frequency array to track characters in the current substring.

- Extend the substring one character at a time and check for duplicates using the frequency array.

- Increment the count for each valid substring and stop extending when a duplicate is found.


### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
countUniqueVisitorSegments(sessionLog) {
    /* Get length of string */
    n = length of sessionLog
    /* Initialize answer */
    ans = 0
    /* Traverse all possible starting points */
    for (i from 0 to n - 1) {
        /* Create frequency array for current substring */
        create freq array of size 26 and initialize with 0
        /* Extend substring from index i */
        for (j from i to n - 1) {
            /* Include current character */
            index = sessionLog[j] - 'a'
            freq[index] = freq[index] + 1
            /* If duplicate found, stop extending */
            if (freq[index] > 1) {
                break
            }
            /* Valid substring with unique characters */
            ans = ans + 1
        }
    }
    /* Return total count */
    return ans
}
```

