### Complexity Analysis

* **Time Complexity:** `O(2^n * 2^k)` 

  * We generate all subsequences of `values`, which gives `2^n` possibilities.

  * For each chosen subsequence of length `k`, the simulation may branch on both left and right removals, leading to up to `2^k` recursive choices in the worst case.

  * So the brute force solution is exponential and becomes impractical for large input sizes.

* **Space Complexity:** `O(n)`

  * We use the `chosen` array to build subsequences and recursion depth can also go up to `n`.

## Solution 2 - Optimal Approach

### Intuition

* After the optional subsequence operation, the remaining elements must still appear in the same order, and during processing we only remove from the two ends. So at any moment, the kept subsequence behaves like some subarray boundary choice inside the original array.

* The DP state `dp[i][j]` represents the maximum number of queries that can already be processed before we are left with the segment `values[i...j]` as the current remaining part.

* To reach `values[i...j]`, the last removed element must have been either `values[i - 1]` from the left side or `values[j + 1]` from the right side. So we transition from larger segments to smaller segments.

* If that last removed element can satisfy the next query, we increase the processed count by `1`; otherwise the processed count stays the same. By taking the best of both choices, we get the maximum number of queries achievable for every remaining segment.

* In the end, once only one element is left, we check whether it can process one more query. The best among all such endings is the final answer.

### Approach

* Create a DP table `dp[i][j]` where each state stores the maximum number of queries already processed before the remaining segment becomes `values[i...j]`.

* Fill this table from larger segments toward smaller segments, because to get `values[i...j]`, the last removed element must have come from just outside this segment.

* Transition from `dp[i - 1][j]` by checking whether `values[i - 1]` can satisfy the next unprocessed query, and similarly transition from `dp[i][j + 1]` using `values[j + 1]`.

* If the removed element is large enough for the next query, increase the processed count by `1`; otherwise keep the same count.

* Take the maximum value from all valid transitions to compute `dp[i][j]`.

* If any state already reaches `m`, return `m` immediately because all queries are processed.

* After filling the table, check all single-element segments and see whether that last remaining value can process one more query.

* Return the maximum processed query count found.


### Pseudo Code

<CodeBlock language={customtext} showNumberOfLines={15} fontStyle={Normal Code}>

```text
maxProcessedQueries(values, limits) {
    n = length of values
    m = length of limits
    answer = 0
    /* dp[i][j] stores maximum queries already processed before remaining segment becomes values[i...j] */
    dp = 2D list of size n x n filled with 0
    /* Process segments from larger outer coverage toward smaller remaining segments */
    for (gap = n - 1 down to 0) {
        for (i = 0 while i + gap < n) {
            j = i + gap
            /* Transition by removing the element just before i */
            if (i > 0) {
                processed = dp[i - 1][j]
                /* If that removed left element can satisfy the next query, increase count */
                if (processed < m and values[i - 1] >= limits[processed]) {
                    dp[i][j] = maximum of dp[i][j] and (processed + 1)
                }
                else {
                    /* Otherwise processed count stays the same */
                    dp[i][j] = maximum of dp[i][j] and processed
                }
            }
            /* Transition by removing the element just after j */
            if (j + 1 < n) {
                processed = dp[i][j + 1]
                /* If that removed right element can satisfy the next query, increase count */
                if (processed < m and values[j + 1] >= limits[processed]) {
                    dp[i][j] = maximum of dp[i][j] and (processed + 1)
                }
                else {
                    /* Otherwise processed count stays the same */
                    dp[i][j] = maximum of dp[i][j] and processed
                }
            }
            /* If all queries are already processed, return immediately */
            if (dp[i][j] == m) {
                return m
            }
        }
    }
    /* Try finishing with every possible single remaining element */
    for (i = 0 to n - 1) {
        processed = dp[i][i]
        /* If the last remaining value can satisfy one more query, count it */
        if (processed < m and values[i] >= limits[processed]) {
            answer = maximum of answer and (processed + 1)
        }
        else {
            answer = maximum of answer and processed
        }
    }
    /* Return the maximum processed query count */
    return answer
}
